Blinken Returns to Israel, Seeking Cease-Fire Momentum

U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken will use trip to the Middle East to press for the quick conclusion of an elusive cease-fire agreement.

The Infants Among the War Dead: Baby Twins Killed in Gaza

With Gaza’s health care system largely reduced to rubble, pregnant women and infants are the most vulnerable.

Fire Breaks Out at London's Somerset House, Home to Priceless Art

Over 125 firefighters worked to douse a fire Saturday at Somerset House, a large central London arts venue that contains priceless works.

Olympic Gold Medal Boxer Imane Khelif Hailed Upon Return to Algeria

With an outpouring of fans greeting her as she arrived in her hometown, boxer Imane Khelif extolled Algeria for backing its athletes.

Proposed Bill Amendment in Iraq Could Allow Girls as Young as 9 to Marry

"If this happens it's probably going to be one of the most impactful events in Iraq's post-2003 history," an expert tells TIME.

Evacuation Ordered in Northern Japan as a Typhoon Approaches

Thousands in northern Japan were ordered to evacuate Friday because of the risk of flooding and mudslides from a typhoon approaching.

What to Know About Paetongtarn Shinawatra, Thailand’s New and Youngest Prime Minister

Known by her nickname Ing, Paetongtarn Shinawatra is the youngest daughter of Thaksin, the patriarch of the political dynasty that has dominated most Thai elections since the turn of the century.

Women Protest on India’s Independence Day After Murder of Medic

As India celebrated 77 years of independence, women around the country marched for justice after a medic's brutal rape and murder.

More than 40,000 Palestinians have been killed in the Israel-Hamas war in Gaza, the territory’s Health Ministry said Thursday.

Vladimir and Evgenia Kara-Murza talked to TIME about the future of Russia after Vladimir was freed in the recent prisoner swap.

It’s Time to Take the Taliban to The Hague

The ICC has the jurisdiction to hold the Taliban accountable, writes Binaifer Nowrojee.

Thai Parliament Taps Paetongtarn Shinawatra as New Prime Minister

The daughter of former Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra was elected by lawmakers to be the country’s new leader after the Constitutional Court removed her predecessor from office.

US-Russian Dual National Jailed for 12 Years on Treason Charges

U.S.-Russian dual national Ksenia Khavana was convicted Thursday of treason in a Russian court and sentenced to 12 years in prison.

Thailand Faces Familiar Political Crisis

The ousting of yet another Prime Minister reflects Thailand’s sorry state of democracy—but change may be on the horizon.

Newborns Killed in Israeli Strike in Gaza

Mohamed Abuel-Qomasan’s newborns were just four days old.
